One approach to classify geothermal systems is with respect to their temperature, enthalpy, and physical state of the fluid (Table 3) (Bodvarsson 1961; Saemundsson et al. 2009). Additionally, they can be also classified based on their geological setting. Following the characterization in Saemundsson et al. (2009), the geothermal systems used for energy production presented in this review are: low- to medium-temperature sedimentary systems and high-temperature volcanic systems.Table 3
Classification of geothermal systems with regard to temperature enthalpy and physical state after Saemundsson et al. (2009); Bodvarsson (1961)

Temperature
Enthalpy
State

Low-temperature (LT) systems with reservoir temperature at 1 km depth below 150∘C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${}^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}. Often characterized by hot and boiling springs.
Low-enthalpy geothermal systems with reservoir fluid enthalpies less than 800 kJkg-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {kJ}\,\hbox {kg}^{-1}$$\end{document}, corresponding to temperatures less than 190∘C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
